what were the open-door notes Open-door notes are a type of communication that takes place between a supervisor and their subordinate. They are typically used to provide feedback and to offer guidance to the subordinate on how they can improve their performance. Open-door notes can also be used to provide clarification on expectations and to provide support to the subordinate.

what were the 'open-door notes' The Open Door Notes were a series of notes sent by the United States to China between 1899 and 1900. The notes were an attempt to establish a relationship between the two countries, and to establish a basis for future trade. The notes were unsuccessful, as China did not want to establish relations with the United States.
